First off let me start by saying I had the most epic weekend at @merusadventure park for the first ever #AdventureHer event! If I had to choose out of all the parks I’ve wheeled at to be my “local park” it would be this one! 

Along with the views the staff is Incredible! @mssmolly thank you for EVERYTHING you have done for me and @mattyj_l7 and for all the ladies who attended this wonderful event! 

Merus offers camping sites, glamping sites, RV sites, and they are currently building some super cool little houses that will also be available  to book once completed! We got the chance to stay in one of their glamping sites that overlooked the canyon and I was just in love! (Be sure to check out the story under my AdventureHer highlight to see) 

The wheeling at this park is out of this world!! The trails are rated similar to the ski slopes. There is green (beginner), blue (intermediate), black (advanced), and purple (buggy rated). During this event I got to spend my time with the “Black Diamonds” as we called ourselves. I met some new faces and also got to wheel with some that are life long friends of mine. 

I loved every minute of it!! 🖤⛰️

Happy Father’s Day to all the Dads out there! Especially this man right here who unfortunately can’t be with his children on this day as they are in the UK. With that being said, as someone who is soon to be married to someone who struggles with mental health, I wanted to shed some light on some things I read up on about Mens Mental health. 

• Nearly 1 in 10 men experience some form of depression or anxiety but less than half seek treatment. 
•The rate of suicide is highest in middle aged men and on average there is 132 suicides per day!

Men often aren’t encouraged to talk about their feelings and sometimes discouraged from doing so. As a child they typically grow up not learning that “skill” of discussing and navigating their feelings. Men are also more solution focused i.e. they hear a problem and jump to the solution to fix it resulting in their emotions being “brushed under the rug”. Lastly they face multiple obstacles that prevent them from opening up. Acknowledgment, openly expressing the struggle, the feeling of shame from “not being man enough to handle it on their own”, and the judgment from society for admitting their weaknesses. 
All of these things in combination are a “recipe for ignoring and hoping the problem goes away.”

June is men’s mental health awareness month and it’s also Fathers Day. Make sure you spend some extra time with your dad or significant other and squeeze them a little tighter not just today but always! We really have no idea what is going on in their mind.🖤

#mensmentalhealth #mensmentalhealthawareness #mensmentalhealthmonth
